Reject the null of equal means when $F>F_{crit}=	ext{F.INV.RT}(\alpha;
u_1;
u_2)$ — equivalently when the p-value $=	ext{F.DIST.RT}(F;
u_1;
u_2)$ is below $\alpha$. Here $\alpha=0.20$ is chosen deliberately high: re-checking an operator's procedure is cheap, so a high first-kind risk is acceptable and it lowers the second-kind risk of missing a real effect.
